Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the Complete Toolchain
Requirement 1
Design an installation sequence that produces a working environment containing: Git, Node.js 18 LTS (via the NodeSource repository), npm, Docker Engine (via the official Docker apt repository), and the Docker Compose plugin. Every tool must be installed from its official upstream source, not from the Ubuntu default apt index, because the default index ships outdated versions that are incompatible with the pipeline configuration you will write in Task 2.

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release
Add the Docker GPG key and repository:

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
Official Docker installation guide if the URL above changes: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

printf 'deb [arch=%s signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu %s stable\n' \
  "$(dpkg --print-architecture)" \
  "$(lsb_release -cs)" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Malformed entry 1 in list file /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â this means a backslash or newline was written literally into the file.
Inspect the file with cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list â it must be a single unbroken line; if it is not, delete it with sudo rm /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list and re-run the printf command above.
Official reference: https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/
Add the NodeSource repository and install Node.js 18:

curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_18.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt-get install -y nodejs
Official NodeSource installation guide if the URL above changes: https://github.com/nodesource/distributions

Troubleshoot this step:

You may see: E: Package 'nodejs' has no installation candidate â this means the NodeSource repository was not added successfully.
Run cat /etc/apt/sources.list.d/nodesource.list and confirm it contains a line beginning with deb; if the file is missing or empty, re-run the curl command above.
Official reference: https://github.com/nodesource/distributions#installation-instructions
Allow your user to run Docker without sudo:

sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
