Task 2: Build the Application, Containerize It, and Publish to Docker Hub
Requirement 1
Design and implement a Node.js web application with the following observable contract: a GET / endpoint that returns a JSON body containing at least the fields message, version, and timestamp; a GET /health endpoint that returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body containing status: "healthy" and a numeric uptime field; any undefined route returns HTTP 404. The application must be accompanied by a test suite (using any Node.js test framework of your choice) that asserts all three of the above behaviors and passes with zero failures when executed locally with a single npm command. The application must also be packaged as a Docker image using a multi-stage or single-stage Dockerfile of your own design, where the final image runs the application as a non-root user and exposes port 3000.

Acceptance criteria:

Running npm test in the project directory exits with code 0 and reports at least five passing assertions covering the /, /health, and 404 behaviors.
Running docker build -t cicd-app:local . followed by docker run -d -p 3000:3000 cicd-app:local and then curl -sf http://localhost:3000/health returns a JSON body where status equals healthy, confirming the containerized application is reachable and the non-root user constraint does not prevent the process from binding to port 3000.
Requirement 2
Design and implement a CircleCI pipeline (.circleci/config.yml) that executes the following jobs in dependency order on every push to the main branch: a unit_test job that installs dependencies and runs the test suite inside a Node.js 18 CircleCI convenience image; an integration_test job that builds the Docker image inside a remote Docker environment and verifies the /health endpoint responds HTTP 200 from within the pipeline runner; a build_and_push job that builds the image tagged with both the CircleCI commit SHA ($CIRCLE_SHA1) and latest, authenticates to Docker Hub using environment variables named DOCKER_USERNAME and DOCKER_PASSWORD stored in CircleCI project settings, and pushes both tags. The build_and_push job must be gated: it must not execute unless both unit_test and integration_test succeed. The pipeline must also emit a plaintext success or failure message as the final step of build_and_push using CircleCI's when: on_success and when: on_fail conditional step syntax so that the outcome is visible in the job log without navigating to Docker Hub.

Acceptance criteria:

After a git push origin main, the CircleCI dashboard shows all three jobs completing with green status, and Docker Hub shows the repository $DOCKER_USERNAME/cicd-app containing two tags: latest and the exact 40-character commit SHA of the triggering commit.
When a deliberate test failure is introduced (by changing one expected assertion value), pushed to main, and then observed in CircleCI, the unit_test job turns red and the build_and_push job does not start, confirming the gate is enforced; after reverting the change and pushing again, all three jobs return to green and both Docker Hub tags are updated.
Expected Outcomes
A fully automated CircleCI pipeline that enforces test passage before publishing any Docker image, producing a versioned and latest-tagged image on Docker Hub for every successful commit to main.
A local integration test script and CircleCI job configuration that together prove the containerized application satisfies its HTTP contract before the image is ever pushed to a registry.
Conclusion
This lab required you to design every component of a container CI/CD pipeline from first principles: the application, its test suite, the Dockerfile, and the CircleCI workflow. The gate-enforced job ordering you implemented is the foundational pattern used in production pipelines to prevent broken images from reaching a registry. Extend this foundation by adding a deployment job that pulls the published image onto a remote server using SSH, which is the natural next step toward a fully automated release process.
